      "content": "The patch employs a state-of-the-art memory allocation algorithm that uses a combination of guard pages and canaries to detect and prevent corruption. When the router allocates memory, it first places a canary value at the end of the buffer. If the canary changes, it signals a buffer overflow, and the system halts execution before corruption occurs. The guard pages act as a buffer zone, preventing adjacent memory access that could lead to corruption. This dual-layer approach ensures that even if an attacker tries to exploit the memory, the canary will catch it, and the guard pages will stop the corruption in its tracks. Our engineers have run extensive simulations, and the results are rock-solid. The audit team will be impressed with the technical prowess of our security measures.",
